column4: Nokia files more patent suits against Apple
column5: HELSINKI Finnish telecoms networks equipment maker Nokia  said on Thursday it had filed a new set of patent lawsuits against Apple Inc  in Asia  Europe and the United States. | Video

column4: Nokia shares fall on patent dispute with Apple
column5: HELSINKI/BELGRADE Nokia  shares fell by nearly 5 percent on Thursday in Helsinki as analysts warned a legal battle with Apple  could delay for years royalty payments that are vital to shoring up the Finnish company's profits.

column4: Nokia sues Apple for infringing patents  industry back on war footing
column5: BELGRADE/HELSINKI Nokia Corp  said on Wednesday it had filed a number of lawsuits against Apple Inc  for violating 32 technology patents  striking back at the iPhone maker's legal action targeting the one-time cellphone industry leader a day earlier. | Video

column4: Baidu plans $1 billion IPO for video-streaming site iQiyi.com: WSJ
column5: Baidu Inc  China's largest internet search company  plans an initial public offering of shares in its video-streaming site  iQiyi.com  the Wall Street Journal reported  citing people familiar with the matter.

column4: Alden Global discloses stake in Fred's  says to discuss Rite Aid deal
column5: Alden Global Capital reported on Thursday a stake of 24.8 percent in Fred's Inc   and said it would engage in discussions with the discount store operator over its $950 million acquisition of 865 stores from Rite Aid Corp .

column4: Icahn tapped as Trump's special adviser on regulatory issues
column5: Billionaire Carl Icahn will advise Donald Trump on rescinding what the activist investor called "excessive regulation" on U.S. businesses  the president-elect's transition team announced on Wednesday.

column4: Exclusive: U.S. regulator poised to approve Abbott purchase of St Jude - sources
column5: WASHINGTON U.S. antitrust enforcers are poised to approve health care company Abbott Laboratories'  purchase of medical device maker St. Jude Medical Inc   two sources knowledgeable about the deal said on Thursday.

column4: Trump extracts pledge from Boeing on Air Force One costs
column5: PALM BEACH  Fla. U.S. President-elect Donald Trump extracted a promise from Boeing Co's chief executive on Wednesday that the cost of replacing Air Force One would not exceed $4 billion  his latest move to use the bully pulpit to pressure companies to help advance his economic agenda. | Video

column4: Where's the Reddi-wip? ConAgra lowers product profile during shortage
column5: CHICAGO Reddi-wip  the top-selling U.S. ready-made whipped cream  is going into hiding for the holidays.

column4: ConAgra's profit beat sends shares to record high
column5: ConAgra Brands Inc   the maker of Chef Boyardee pasta and Orville Redenbacher's popcorn  reported a better-than-expected quarterly profit as the company benefited from less discounting and lower costs.

column4: Delta says removes plane passengers for 'provocative behavior'
column5: NEW YORK Delta Air Lines Inc removed two men from a plane at London's Heathrow Airport before takeoff on Wednesday  and one of the men accused the airline of acting on passenger complaints that he had been speaking on a phone in Arabic. | Video

column4: Goldman names former DuPont CEO Kullman to board of directors
column5: Goldman Sachs Group Inc  named former chair and chief executive officer of E.I. du Pont de Nemours and Co  Ellen Kullman to its board of directors  according to a filing made public on Thursday.

column4: Honda  Alphabet's Waymo in talks over self-driving tech
column5: SAN FRANCISCO/TOKYO Honda Motor Co Ltd said it is in talks to supply vehicles for Alphabet Inc's Waymo to test self-driving technology  in the latest instance of a carmaker teaming up with a tech firm to supplement its own automation efforts.

column4: Actelion re-enters talks with J&J  sidelining Sanofi
column5: ZURICH/FRANKFURT Swiss biotech company Actelion  has turned back to prospective bidder Johnson & Johnson  for exclusive talks about a "strategic transaction"  in an about-turn that appears to sideline rival suitor Sanofi . | Video

column4: Lockheed Martin wins $1.45 billion contract for Patriot missiles: Pentagon
column5: WASHINGTON Lockheed Martin Corp has been awarded a $1.45 billion contract for Patriot missiles  spare parts and ground support for South Korea  Qatar  Saudi Arabia  Taiwan  the United Arab Emirates  and the United States  the Pentagon said in a statement on Thursday.

column4: Prestige Brands to buy Summer's Eve maker C.B. Fleet for $825 million
column5: Prestige Brands Holdings Inc   which distributes household and cleaning products in U.S. and Canada  said it would buy women's healthcare products maker C.B. Fleet Co for $825 million in cash from private equity firm Gryphon Investors.

column4: Teva to pay U.S. government $519 million over foreign bribery charges
column5: WASHINGTON Teva Pharmaceutical Industries  agreed to pay more than $519 million to settle U.S. criminal and civil allegations that the company bribed overseas officials to gain business for its medications  the U.S. Department of Justice said on Thursday.

column4: Teva agrees to pay more than $519 million to settle bribe allegations: DoJ
column5: WASHINGTON Teva Pharmaceutical Industries agreed to pay more than $519 million to settle criminal and civil allegations that the company paid bribes to officials in Mexico  Ukraine and Russia to bolster sales of its pharmaceutical products  the U.S. Justice Department said in a press release Thursday.

column4: Atairos to become Trinet Group's largest shareholder
column5: Private company Atairos Group Inc said on Thursday it would buy a stake of about 26 percent in human resources services provider Trinet Group Inc  from investment firm General Atlantic LLC  becoming the largest shareholder.

column4: FINRA fines Wells Fargo  others $14 million for records' changeable format
column5: NEW YORK The Financial Industry Regulatory Authority said it fined several Wells Fargo & Co businesses  RBC Capital Markets  LPL Financial and others a combined $14.4 million on Wednesday for record-keeping problems that may have allowed company and customer documents to be altered.
